Problem Statement and Data Dictionary¶

The data is about customers of the treadmill product(s) of a retail store called Cardio Good Fitness. It contains the following variables Product - The model no. of the treadmill Age - Age of the customer in no of years Gender - Gender of the customer Education - Education of the customer in no. of years Marital Status - Marital status of the customer Usage - Avg. # times the customer wants to use the treadmill every week Fitness - Self rated fitness score of the customer (5 - very fit, 1 - very unfit) Income - Income of the customer Miles- Miles that a customer expects to run

7.2DataType Conversions¶

To better be able to analize the data, we can convert the Gender and MaritalStatus features to binary, and also assign a code(1,2,3) to Product types. Also we can create a dataframe for each product to better understand the customer profile of each individually.

In [9]:
numerical_data=data.copy()
numerical_data['Gender'].replace(to_replace=['Male', 'Female'], value=[0, 1], inplace=True)
numerical_data['MaritalStatus'].replace(to_replace=['Single', 'Partnered'], value=[0, 1], inplace=True)
numerical_data['Product'].replace(to_replace=['TM195', 'TM498', 'TM798'], value=[1, 2, 3], inplace=True)

product1_data=numerical_data[numerical_data['Product']==1]
product2_data=numerical_data[numerical_data['Product']==2]
product3_data=numerical_data[numerical_data['Product']==3]

**Observation**: Type of the Product is correlated most strongly to Income, then Fitness, Miles, Usage and Education. Miles is strongly correlated with Usage and Fitness at 0.76 and 0.79 which is expected. Income is correlated with Education at 0.63, also slightly correlated with Age at 0.51, Usage at 0.52 and with Miles and Fitness at 0.54. It is surprising to see that Fitness and Age are not inversely correlated at 0.06. There seems to be an inverse correlation between Gender and Usage, Fitness, Income and Miles. It also shows Females tend to buy first two products more than the third(TM798). MaritalStatus seems to not correlate or affect any other feature. We will investigate these results to form more insight and conclusion.

Insights, Conclusions and Recommendations:¶

Age, Income and Education level are correlated. Usage, Miles and Fitness are correlated.

Marital Status was not a predictor in product or usage patterns.

Most of customers belong to 20-30 year old age group. Since this is a fitness equipment, there is a lot of potential to gain customers from other age groups. Might need to change advertisement method to target and reach other age groups.

Data shows that Products TM195 and TM498 seem to apeal to both genders since they have similar number of customers, but product TM798 has much fewer female customers (33 Males to 7 Females). Since this product is also correlates to customers that have rated themselves with a higher Fitness level, maybe the marketing approach is turning away potential amature customers by advertising for professionals only. Data also suggests that customers that want to run more Miles, and predicted higher number of weekly Usage, are more likely to buy TM798.

Higher Income correlates to age, higher Education, and increases the likelihood of a customer buying TM798.

The Fitness measure was provided by customers and is not a great measure. Contrary to what we would expect, shows that customers in age group 40-50 have rated themselves with highest average Fitness rating. There's a difference between Males and Females in that Females have reported lower Fitness ratings in total across all age groups.
